It caught my eye as it had a factory flash suppressor, which was unavailable on civilian model Mini 14s at the time.  The dealer said that it was a limited edition and Ruger made 1000 of them, and the largest Ruger dealers got two each.  I have never seen another one like it. title: For Sale:  RARE! ALBANIAN SKS “JULY 10TH RIFLE” 7.62X39CAL
location: East Bend (336)692-0317 sog, Winston Salem, North Carolina
postcontent:
The Albanian SKS were produced at the Umgramsh factory from 1967 through 1979. Only about 18,000 of these gas powered semi-automatic carbines were manufactured. It is believed that fewer than 6,000 survived destruction during the UN-led disarming initiative after the Balkan wars. The Albanian SKS has a longer handguard than most SKS’s, an AK-style charging handle, a buttplate with two trapdoors instead of one, a Y shaped folding spike bayonet instead of the more traditional x shaped cruciform, a differently-contoured magazine than other SKS’s, and a sling swivel on the left side of the buttstock.The Albanians called their SKS the “July 10th” Rifle, named after the anniversary of the centralization of the Albanian National Liberation Army in 1942 to fend off fascist Italy. We have obtained a very small quantity of these rare SKS military rifle. These won’t last long!

Overall excellent condition, with extremely minor wear--the sort of almost invisible surface scratches that are inevitable on high polish stainless. The action is very smooth and timing excellent. This is the dash -4 version meaning it is made before S&W implemented its internal trigger lock and the cheaper MIM parts found in today's Smith & Wessons. The dash 4 is considered by most to be the ultimate vintage for a standard production 686, which is itself considered by many to be the ultimate .357 caliber revolver, at least in this price range.

I happened across a second 686 so now I have doubles and no need for this one. I'm looking to trade it for something I don't already have instead. I'll consider just about any offer, but I'll include a partial list of things I'm particularly interested in of relatively equal value for reference.

I may be willing to throw in an Alessi Fieldmaster shoulder holster rig to make the right trade happen. The holster portion swivels inside of a sheath for easy draw and had two speed loader pouches opposite. These cost $235 new.

Must have valid Alabama driver's license for FTF trade. Having a CCW permit is a nice reassurance as well.
